     <int-org-section id="PIF-SEC.IO.116" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
          <heading>Organization</heading>
          <heading-note>April 2024</heading-note>
          <int-org-section id="PIF.SEC.IO.117.1" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Leaders’ Forum</heading>
               <p>An annual Leaders' Forum is hosted by the country holding the organization’s rotating chairmanship. The 52nd Forum was convened in the Cook Islands, in November 2023, in two sessions: a Leaders Plenary, held in Rarotonga, following by a Leaders’ Retreat, in Aitutaki. The 53rd Forum was to be hosted by Tonga in August 2024. Decisions of the Forums are reached by consensus.</p>
               <p>A Special Leaders’ Retreat was convened, virtually, in early February 2021 to appoint a new Secretary-General, and to consider progress in managing the coronavirus situation, the impacts of climate change, oceanscape issues, and other regional challenges. In February 2023, under the outgoing Fijian chairmanship, a Special Leaders’ Retreat was convened to reinforce and demonstrate renewed Pacific unity. A Forum Troika, comprising the current, previous and next chairmanships, became operational in August.</p>
               <!--~ 2025: Solomon Islands-->
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="IO-PIF.001" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Ministerial Meetings</heading>
               <p>Since 2016 Forum ministers responsible for foreign affairs have met annually to discuss strengthening regionalism and relevant foreign policy matters. The 2023 meeting was held in September, in Suva. Forum economic affairs ministers meet annually to address regional economic development and policy matters. The Cook Islands, Kiribati, Federated States of Micronesia, Marshall Islands, Nauru, Niue, Palau and Tuvalu participate in the Forum Smaller Island States (SIS) economic sub-group, which convenes an annual summit meeting to address their specific smaller island concerns. In February 2021 the Forum leaders agreed to establish a standing Pacific Forum Women Leaders Meeting and Forum Trade Ministerial Meeting.</p>
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="PIF-SEC.IO.117" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Forum Officials Committee (FOC)</heading>
               <p>The FOC comprises one representative from each member country. It meets twice a year, immediately before the Leaders’ Forum Meeting and at the end of the year, to discuss in detail the Secretariat's work programme, and policy directions and annual budget, and to make recommendations and reports to the Forum leaders.</p>
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="PIF-SEC.IO.118" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Secretariat</heading>
               <p>
        The Secretariat is headed by a Secretary-General and has a staff of some 70 people appointed from the member countries. There are Programme Directors for Governance and Engagement, Policy, Operations, and Programme Initiatives. A Pacific ACP/EU Co-operation unit assists member states and regional organizations with submitting projects to the 
        <xr pageref="N" ref="WB02047.IO.TXT">EU</xr>
        . An SIS unit was established within the Secretariat in 2006. The Secretariat chairs the 
        <xr pageref="N" ref="OTHER.IO.FEA.37">Council of Regional Organizations in the Pacific,</xr>
         an ad hoc committee comprising the heads of nine regional organizations, which aims to discuss and co-ordinate the policies and work programmes of the various agencies in order to avoid duplication of or omissions in their services to member countries. 
      </p>
               <p>In accordance with the Suva Agreement, signed by Forum leaders in June 2022, a Forum subregional office was to be opened in Kiribati and a new role of Pacific Ocean Commissioner was to be established, based in Palau.</p>
